15	Clear Blue Sea: Solar-powered, semi-autonomous Floating Robot For Eliminating Debris (FRED) that cleans oceans	2016	840	Non-Profit Org	Prototype	t	\N	national	[]	Description: Our Concept of Operations is to implement fleets of 100s of FREDs, ranging in size from 50-100 feet, for cleanup of the Great Pacific Garbage Patch, coastlines, bays, estuaries, and rivers. FREDs will operate autonomously in the ocean gyres, except when they need human intervention, at which point the Clear Blue Sea staff in our mission control center will take over FRED navigation and perform remote control of FREDs operations and routing.\n\nFREDs architecture is comprised of a simple set of subsystems:\n\nVESSEL PLATFORM SUBSYSTEM  \nThe supporting elements of FREDs architecture are the hulls and cross beams, which support debris collection and power, and enable FRED to float in marine environments. Hulls can be made from various materials, such as commercial pontoons or fiberglass hulls, or they can be made from raw materials.\t\n\nDEBRIS COLLECTION SUBSYSTEM \nFRED utilizes booms, belts, and bins to capture and store floating marine plastic and debris polluting the environment. The booms, which are floating arms attached to the hull frame, guide floating plastic pollution up onto the conveyor belt, and can be made of plastic, metal, or composite material. The conveyor belt, which is powered by motors receiving electricity from the Power Subsystem, is attached to the hull frame for stability. Marine debris is taken by FREDs conveyor belt to an embedded storage bin, which is sized appropriately for one mission and is able to drain water to lighten the load. \n\nPOWER SUBSYSTEM \nFRED is designed to use sustainable energy. To capture the suns energy, FRED utilizes an array of marine-worthy solar panels forming the roof of the vessel. Solar panels can be in the form of flexible, malleable material, or rigid planes that are individually framed. Onboard batteries store electrical energy generated from the solar panels.\n\nNAVIGATION SUBSYSTEM \nFREDs hulls are propelled forward using electrical motors which receive electricity from the solar panel/battery assembly. Propulsion by the motors can be made autonomous or performed via remote control.\n\nSENSOR SUBSYSTEM \nFREDs architecture provides a platform for embedding scientific sensors and instrumentation to be used for collecting data and samples from the environment. Some sensors provide performance information, such as FREDs speed and location, and other sensors capture weather data, such as air and water temperature, wind speed, and current strength. FREDs sensors are powered by solar energy.\n\nDATA COMMUNICATIONS SUBSYSTEM\nWhile FRED is in marine environments, its data communications capability enables commands to be transmitted from ground control to FRED and operational data to be transmitted from FRED to ground control. This enables remote control, navigational routes, and display of FRED operational data. \n\nOur 50-foot FRED is designed to deliver the following enhanced capabilities per our system requirements baseline:\n\tCollect floating marine plastic and debris ranging in size from 5mm to 5 meters on a 24/7 basis\n\tPropel at 2 knots to prevent unannounced infringement on marine life\n\tNavigate autonomously based on GPS trajectory commands from mission control staff\n\tNavigate under remote control during unsafe conditions (storms, etc.)\n\tUtilize only solar power for FRED operations with stored energy available on cloudy days  \n\tProvide excess stored energy to governmental and commercial marine Underwater Autonomous Vehicles (UAVs) for recharging their batteries without having to return to land\n\tAlert marine mammals of FRED proximity using appropriate acoustic pingers recommended by marine scientists at Scripps Institute of Oceanography\n\tCapture environmental, oceanographic, and marine ecosystem data in real-time for transmittal to designated scientific, governmental, and commercial information systems\n\tTransmit sensor and instrumentation data to ground-based mission control systems for Clear Blue Sea staff to monitor, govern, and control fleets of FREDs as required\n\nPlastic recovery capacity: A scaled-up version of FRED (50 feet long by 30 feet wide), which will be used in Hawaii for our Phase III Pilot Program, will collect an estimated 750 cubic yards of plastic, per FRED, per year. Using the weight of a large plastic bottle, this equates to 56,250 pounds of collected plastic each year, for each FRED in the fleet. 	2021-04-28 06:24:45.831781+00	2021-10-04 15:28:46.904294+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://clearbluesea.org/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_015.png	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_15_logo.png	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
