43	ReCleanSea: Industrial solutions for ocean plastics collection & recycling	2018	250	Non-Profit Org	Development	f	contact@recleansea.org	national	[]	ReCleanSea is a non-profit organisation that is developing a unique system designed to clean up, on an industrial level, large polluted regions where floating plastic trash has accumulated with currents, winds or waves in rivers, estuaries or coastal areas. Leveraging 15+ years of experience collecting trash and heavy oil at sea and in freshwaters with small to mid-size collectors, they are building a massive apparatus. \n\nThey leverage their founders 20-year experience in designing, building and operating industrial systems to tow extra-wide underwater imaging tools, as well as oil and plastic trash collectors, like the 150 small ones that the French Navy uses to protect the French coasts from oil spills.\n\nThe trash collectors can be anchored in rivers or estuaries, or towed by one or two fishing or work boats in any area, after a simple half-day training session. As such, they can benefit any local community all over the world.\n\nTheir proof of concept consists in building an extra-wide collector, to be towed by an existing ship, itself modified to accommodate an onboard plastic treatment unit for sorting the trash and possibly testing some recycling features. Their XXL collector is scalable, thanks to parts that are 100 m wide each, which allows it to reach 500 m in width and 700 m in length.\nTowed by the ship in various sea conditions during their test campaign, the extra-wide collector will sweep a large area polluted with ocean plastics. Plastic debris will accumulate in the filtering net at the tip of the collector, which is pulled back to the ship when full. Once onboard, the filtering net will be emptied onto the ship, and the plastic will be sorted and processed for recycling, while the filtering net will return to sea for another sweep.\n\nThe collectors have never caught any fish in 15 years of operation. When they are towed, its at the very slow speed of 2 knots, which gives fish plenty of time to feel the draft and move away, especially as the immersed skirts of the collector are not deep. When the collectors are anchored in a river, they also let any marine life escape the current towards the filtering net.\n\nFounding partners have contributed to a starting budget to promote the project and look for investors. They are in talks with different public and private entities, internationally, to wrap their budget.\n\nThey estimate the cost of the extra-wide collector alone at 800K. Adding the cost of research and studies, of modifying the ship to accommodate a treatment unit and of course the cost of the test campaign at sea, they have budgeted 5M for the proof of concept.\n\nAs for any trash collection and recycling process, they believe in a combination of two main factors to make this a sustainable business model:\n\nThere is a specific market for recycled ocean plastic as a raw material, with higher value than land plastic.\nConsidering the actual cost of plastic pollution, loss of revenues from fisheries and tourism, and serious damages to the environment, they believe that ocean plastic recovery, even subsidised, is a matter of survival for natural ecosystems and mankind.\nThey aim to build the collector in 2019 and have the test campaign at sea in 2019-2020.\n\nThey are looking for partners and investors to support the first series of tests of the proof of concept and to support the association. \nThey can be reached at  +33 7 61 09 23 51 or via email at contact@ReCleanSea.org\n	2021-04-28 06:24:46.558199+00	2021-10-04 15:28:47.000609+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	http://www.recleansea.org	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_043.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_43_logo.jpeg	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
