42	Project STOP: Creating a comprehensive waste management system to stop ocean plastics leakage	\N	360	Partnerships	In market	t	info@stopoceanplastics.com	national	[]	Description: The world is struggling to answer the question: How do we stop ocean plastic leakage permanently, and do so as quickly and efficiently as possible? Permanent reduction results from solving the complex root causes behind mismanaged waste, deeply tied to the interwoven economic, regulatory, technical, social and behavioural norms of a region. Solutions need to be found that are culturally appropriate, inclusive, economically sustainable, technically rigorous, and built on a foundation of transparent, reliable governance, all of which takes time to develop. Yet, we are in a plastic crisis and need to move and scale quickly without neglecting the fundamental building blocks required for systemic change.  \nTo do this, first, we must focus our time and resources where it matters most - on the locations with the highest pollution levels coupled with strong government and local commitment. We then need to unearth local collective wisdom and leadership, to quickly get to what will work and co-develop a plan forward that everyone can stand behind to develop economically sustainable, circular, "zero leakage" waste systems. We also need to ensure sufficient revenue is available to cover the costs of each waste system, especially in Indonesia where waste funding is generally insufficient.\nProject STOPpartners with cities and local government to build resilient and economically sustainable waste systems that eliminate leakage of plastics into the environment and ocean. \nNearly 80% of plastic waste in aquatic ecosystems comes from land sources. About 50% of this comes from emerging countries like Indonesia, China, Philippines, Vietnam and Thailand. Project STOP aims to assist countries like Indonesia who have pledged to reduce the country ocean levels by 70% by 2025. This is to be done by helping establish an effective waste management system in the country. \nLaunched in 2017, Project STOP is an initiative co-founded by Borealis and SYSTEMIQ that designs, implements, and scales circular economy solutions to prevent plastic pollution in Southeast Asia. Project STOP supports cities with experiencedwaste management, plastic recycling, organic waste management, community engagement, behavior change and program governance experts. The team works in a simple system: \n\tScoping: Assessing cities for ocean pollution and government involvement. \n\tPreparation & Design:Stakeholder agreements to build an effective waste management system. \n\tImplementation:Equip the community to operate the waste management system economically. \n\tScale Up:Expanding to new regions to establish change. \nWorking with companies, local governments and community groups, Project STOP also aims o create new jobs in waste management and reduce the harmful impact of mismanaged waste on public health, tourism and fisheries. Project STOPs long-term ambition is to establish new solutions and models that can be rapidly scaled-up across the whole plastics chain, from the uses of plastic to waste collection and recycling, in areas where there is need to improve the management of plastic waste. Project STOP currently works in the coastal cities of  Muncar (Population: 130,000 inhabitants) in East Java, Lekok and Ngulign in Pasuruan (Population: 130,000 inhabitants) in East Java, and Jembrana (Population: 160,000 inhabitants) in northwest Bali. \nAlong with co-founders SYSTEMIQandBorealis, Project Stops strategic partners include the Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Nova Chemicals, Nestl, Alliance to End Plastic Waste and Borouge.\n\nPlastic recovery capacity: We collect all the plastic waste generated. We sort it and based on our capture rate (40-70% - depending on facility) and our available markets we sell the plastic to aggregators. In Indonesia, a city of 100k people produce annually ~1,500 tons of plastics. Our aim is to achieve >90% collection coverage within 2 years. 	2021-04-28 06:24:46.545257+00	2021-10-04 15:28:45.227329+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.stopoceanplastics.com/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_042.jpg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_42_logo.jpeg	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
