55	Trash Wheel	\N	840	Established Company	In market	t	\N	national	[]	Description: Storm sewers and feeder streams carry trash-laden runoff to rivers that flow to harbors, bays, and oceans. The Trash Wheel harnesses renewable energy to collect and remove trash and debris from a flowing waterway. Containment booms funnel the floating trash and debris to a conveyor.  A waterwheel provides mechanical power to the conveyor using energy from the river current and solar powered pumps.  The trash is lifted by the conveyor and deposited into a dumpster. The conveyor and waterwheel are mounted on a floating platform that is held in place by pilings.  The dumpster is located on a separate barge, which is pushed by a service vessel to a transfer point for disposal.  A covering structure over the conveyor and dumpster prevents trash from being blown by the wind, protects the equipment, and provides a support structure for the photovoltaic panels. The covering structure is adapted to the specific location to optimize the power generation by the solar panels.  The machine also features an internet based remote control and monitoring system which uses cameras to monitor the trash flow and the dumpster level as well as web based controls which allow the pumps to be turned on or off from a smart phone or a computer from anywhere the internet is available.\n  \nOur flagship model in Baltimore collects trash and debris from the Jones Falls River, the largest tributary to the citys Inner Harbor.  Its floating platform is 50 long by 24 wide and constructed of quarter inch epoxy coated steel.  The waterwheel is 14 in diameter and constructed of precision cut galvanized steel.  The 36 long conveyor is submerged to a depth of 2 feet at the upstream end; and fills a 15-18 cubic yard roll-off dumpster.  The solar power is generated from a 3 kilowatt array and powers 9 pumps capable of moving more than 25,000 gallons per hour.  Clearwater Mills also offers both larger and smaller models to fit