49	The Great Bubble Barrier: A proven concept to reduce river plastics and an elegant bubbly solution to a worldwide problem.	2015	528	Startup	Scale up	f	\N	national	[]	The founders of The Great Bubble Barrier believe plastic waste can be caught before it reaches the oceans.\n\nToo much of the waste that our society produces ends up in the water, where it damages marine and human life. Sea turtles and fish get caught up in plastic, ships are obstructed in their paths, and micro plastics form a health hazard for the smallest to the largest organisms. Plastic soup is recognized as an international problem more and more, by both the public, municipalities, government and the European Union. The current solutions that stop waste in the rivers have two major drawbacks unfortunately; they block ship traffic and/or hinder fish movement.\n\nThe Great Bubble Barrier team searched for an elegant solution that blocks waste in the river, but also allows the passage of fish and ships. They arrived at a very simple idea: a barrier of bubbles.\n\nThe Great Bubble Barrier offers a solution for different problem-owners: it can help governments meet changing regulation on waste management in waterways, but also help cities fight plastic problems in their waters and help waterboards to save on their cleanups after high water. \n\nThe three co-founders of the Great Bubble Barrier, Anne Marieke Eveleens, Francis Zoet and Saskia Studer, all have a big passion for sailing and nature. This is what inspired them to look for a fitting solution to the plastic soup, both fish & ship friendly.\n\nThey have successfully run pilots in partnership with Deltares, Rijkswaterstaat & BAM / VandenHerik,  and are supported by sustainable & offshore organizations like Sustainable Young 100, Our Oceans Challenge, By The Ocean We Unite and the Plastic Soup Foundation. \n\nThe Bubble Barrier intercepts 1 mm plastics in rivers and canals, and the team will further explore the possibilities and impact of our Bubble Barrier on microplastics coorperating with a research consortium formed by PWN (a drinking water company), KWR (research institut) and Hoogheemraadschap Hollands Noorderkwartier (HHNK - water management board). This consortium is starting a study to prevent microplastics from purified wastewater from flowing into surface water. With this, the consortium is taking a step towards clarifying the nature of the cause and reducing the occurrence of microplastics in surface water as they can pose a threat to people and the environment.\n\nThe new Bubble Barrier installed in Wervershoof will give an insight into the physical effect of the Bubble Barrier on microplastics with a size of 0.5 mm to 0.02 mm.\n\nAs 8 of the 10 most polluted rivers in the world, are located in Asia, the team want to bring The Great Bubble Barrier there as soon as possible and are hoping to start there in a couple of years from now. The first steps, and contacts have been made.	2021-04-28 06:24:46.673996+00	2021-10-04 15:28:46.173761+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://thegreatbubblebarrier.com/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_049.gif	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_49_logo.png	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
20	AlphaMERS :Floating trash barriers, simple trash collection  system on rivers	2010	356	Established Company	Scale up	t	\N	national	[]	Description: This is a passive system and does not require external energy for working. The water surface velocity does the job. It is secured on both banks or one end is anchored in water as necessary. It is deployed where the stream crosses a road or has road access. The alignment ensures that the plastics and biota lies close to one bank within reach of riverbank based gear. Boats and floating gear is not required to evacuate the collection. Floating plastics, wood, biota etc is captured by this system and mesh opening size is 10 cm x 10 cm, though it can be customized.  Where boat traffic exists the alignment can allow boat movement while  arresting trash and plastics. The alignment is different in tidal streams.  We have different models for river, stream, and smaller drains. All of them are passive systems.\n\nPlastic recovery capacity: This has recovered 22000 Tons of trash including 2200 Tons of Plastics in one year in one river. This data is as per the municipal corporation records and has been published in Media. \nhttps://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/a-mountain-of-trash-fished-out-of-cooum/article26115438.ece	2021-04-28 06:24:45.955141+00	2021-10-04 15:28:46.547207+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.alphamers.com	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_020.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_20_logo.jpeg	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
9	Bandalong Litter Trap: Proven solution for floatables control	2006	840	Established Company	In market	t	sales@stormwatersystems.com	national	[]	Description: The Bandalong Litter Traps and StormX Netting Trash Traps are passive capturing systems that require no energy other than the natural current or flow.  The Bandalong is used in creeks, rivers, canals, or channel waterways to capture floating litter and debris and DOES NOT harm aquatic species or wildlife. \nStormX is an end-of -pipe netting systems that can be used on pipe out falls, structures, and in channels to capture both floatables and non-floatables. StormX is not used in live streams where aquatic species and wildlife are present.\nBoth products are proven internationally for over 20 years!\n\nPlastic recovery capacity: The BANDALONG LITTER TRAP will capture floating litter and debris 24/7 without mechanical assistance. It has unlimited capacity to capture floatables using our unique boom configuration with the trap without restriction of flow or harm to aquatic species or wildlife. Examples: Washington, DC first litter small Bandalong trap captured 6 tons the first year.  A large Bandalong in Mobile, AL 500 cubic yards the first year.\nNOTE: WITH THE UNIQUE DESIGN OF THE BANDALONG THE AMOUNTS COLLECTED DEPENDS ON THE AMOUNT OF TRASH FLOWING IN THE WATER THE CAPACITY IS UNLIMITED.\n\nSTORMX capacity depends on the diameter of the  out flow pipe and the length of the net. All StormX installations need consideration for overflow/bypass options when nets are full of trash and debris. 	2021-04-28 06:24:45.706287+00	2021-10-04 15:28:46.708374+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://stormwatersystems.com/bandalong-litter-trap/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_009.jpg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_09_logo.PNG	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
59	Fishing for Litter: Ocean cleaning project that involves fishermen who collect debris during fishing activities	1990	826	Non-Profit Org	In market	f	info@kimo.shetland.org	national	[]	KIMO International works with fishermen to clean the seas, by providing them with large bags to collect litter, which is then recycled or disposed.\n\nMarine pollution is one of the biggest environmental concerns worldwide. Not only does it add to the growing pollution levels across the world, but also endangers marine and human lives, who are dependent on oceans for their living. Marine pollution also affects the livelihood of fishermen, through reduced fishing opportunities.\n\nThe Fishing for Litter project was initiated by KIMO International at a single port in the Netherlands, and it has grown and spread across Europe. European Organisations such as OSPAR have endorsed the program and encourages its 15 member countries to take part in it actively, as a part of its Regional Action Plan against marine litter.\n\nThe Fishing for Litter team provides fishing vessels with large bags to collect plastics and other debris from the oceans, which gathers in their nets during their fishing activities.\nWhen the fishing boats return to port, they offload the collected waste to Fishing for Litter volunteers who either recycle the waste or dispose it suitably.\nThe goal of the Fishing for Litter team is to promote cleaner seas, cleaner beaches, and a better marine environment for all marine lives and humans.\nMore than 1,000 fishing vessels are now involved in this project from 8 countries across Europe and 450 tonnes of plastic and other waste was recovered from the oceans in 2016-17.\n\nEncouraged by the response of this initiative, the EU has revised its Port Reception Facilities Directive to make a special provision and space for the Fishing for Litter project. This will encourage more ports and ships to be a part of this project.\n\nAll ports and shipping vessels that would like the oceans and seas to be cleaner can be a part of this initiative.\n	2021-04-28 06:24:46.835308+00	2021-10-04 15:28:47.094783+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://fishingforlitter.org/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_059.jpg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_59_logo.jpg	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
18	Empower: Blockchain based model to pay people who collect waste plastic all over the world	2018	578	Startup	In market	f	hi@empower.eco	national	[]	Based on the idea of using technology to enable a circular economy and create a cleaner and better world, Empower was founded in January 2018. They are building a global plastic waste platform and are present in more than 20 countries throughout Europe, Africa and Asia.\n\nEmpower is built on the same philosophy as the Norwegian bottle deposit system (which ensures 97% of bottles being recycled). By rewarding deposit of plastic waste, they can stop leakage of plastic into the environment, and crowdsource the collection and sorting at source of leaked waste.\n\nTheir mission is that people can pick up plastic waste anywhere in the world, deliver it at a collection point and immediately receive a reward. \nThe use of Blockchain technology ensures full transparency. They are able to track and link every deposit of plastic back to the sponsor who made it possible - thus laying the ground for real Producer Responsibility and digital Deposit Return Schemes (dDRS)\n\nEmpower is also tracking the collected and registred plastic through the value chain to see where the collected plastic ends up and also making it possible for producers of recycled plastic products to show where the recycled materials is coming from while proving it is done in a responsible and socially good way. \n\nThe startup is dedicated to be fully transparent in both how plastic waste collection is funded, the social and environmental impact and also where all recycled plastics are coming from and their journey from collection to new product. Empowers platform is a part of the digital infrastructure that the world needs to move from a linear to a circular economy and already in its early years we see the signs of global impact.	2021-04-28 06:24:45.922093+00	2021-10-04 15:28:47.170318+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://empower.eco/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_018.jpg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_18_logo.jpg	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
61	Ocean Polymers: Building a plastic recycling plant in the ocean to convert plastic into power.	2017	826	Startup	Research	f	info@oceanpolymers.co.uk	national	[]	Ocean Polymers is committed to turning plastic waste into a valuable resource. \n\nThe startup is constructing a tanker, named OP3 with a gasification system that has the capacity of processing 200 tons of plastic and waste per day thanks to its onboard machinery which recycles plastic found in the ocean and converts it into hydrogen to power the station. \n\nThe firm has been working with a team from Imperial College London on the project for the past six years, and it hopes to get up and running in the second half of 2019. \n\nDuring the recycling process on the ship, valuable products such as hydrogen, synthetic gases, building materials and substrates will be created. Their systems will not only remove plastics which are harmful to marine wildlife and enter the food chain but it is self-funding when operating, as a result of the valuable bi-products created.\n\nThe project will involve smaller boats traveling short distances to take rubbish back to the main ship. \n\nOcean Polymers has secured the patent pending status that has been granted by the US Patent Office on 14th May 2019.  They are in the process of securing intellectual property rights and developing a business plan.	2021-04-28 06:24:46.864195+00	2021-10-04 15:28:47.342365+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.cleanourocean.com	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_061.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_61_logo.png	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
7	# tide ocean material: A global supply chain for 100% upcycled ocean bound plastic waste	\N	756	Startup	In market	f	hello@tide.earth	national	[]	Tide Ocean Material transforms the plastics threatening our oceans into new sustainable products. Through it's global supply chain it provides eco-conscious brand with a sustainable premium raw material made from 100% ocean bound plastic. Thus, helping to close the circle of plastic consumption and showing that waste has value.\n\nTogether with social enterprises, they are collecting ocean-bound plastic in Southeast Asia, coordinated by a #tide subsidiary in Ranong, Thailand. On five islands in the Andaman Sea, local fishermen are being trained and paid to gather and sort plastic waste. The material is registered, washed and shredded in a social enterprise which is being implemented by the Swiss non-profit Jan & Oscar Foundation and the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN).   \n\nThey collect PET, polypropylene, and polyethylene. With Swiss precision, know-how and with the help of clean solar energy, the plastic waste is upcycled into a versatile granular material. The award-winning method was developed in close partnership with the University of Applied Sciences in Switzerland. It is a strictly mechanical process, no chemicals are being added and no virgin plastic is processed whatsoever. The #tide granules are used for plastic injection for watches, furniture, electronic devices, automotive parts and any type of hard plastic product. The #tide yarn can be used for any high quality polyester textile, such as apparel, bags, shoes, home & office interiors. #tide filament can be used for 3D-printing.	2021-04-28 06:24:45.658115+00	2021-10-04 15:28:47.456843+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://tide.earth/#home	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_007.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_07_logo.jpeg	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
39	Plasticoin: Virtual currency in exchange for plastic waste	2020	858	Startup	Pilot	f	info@plasticoin.com.uy	national	[]	Plasticoin is a project in Uruguay that uses virtual currency to incentivize consumers to recycle plastic waste. The currency can be used at restaurants and stores.\n\nNearly 13 million tonnes of plastic waste is not recycled and ends up in the worlds oceans, according to the United Nations. In Uruguay, a country of 3.4 million people, only 35% of plastic waste is collected for recycling.\n\nPlasticoin aims to incentivize consumers to deposit their plastic waste in return for virtual currency. The project is undergoing pilot tests at a seaside resort in Piriapolis city on the countrys Atlantic Ocean coast:\n\nConsumers can register online and deposit plastic waste from their household or collected from the beach at one of the three designated collection centers. \nThey receive Plasticoin currency on their phone based on the weight and type of waste discarded. The minimum waste is one kg, for which they receive Plasticoins. To promote clean coastal zones, plastic waste and microplastic removed from beaches and oceans results in a higher Plasticoin payment.\nThe customers can use the currency to get discounts at partnered shops and restaurants. These include yoga centers, surfboard shops, and shops selling bags, toothbrushes, pizza, haircuts, and coffee, among other products.\nPlasticoins launched in January 2020 with a grant of $5000 from the Uruguan governments National Development Agency. The project received more than a thousand users within three weeks, against a target of 100 users in a month.\n\nThe project is looking for companies that can provide discounts on their products to Plasticoin users. It is also looking for companies to advertise on the Plasticoin platform. Based on the number of Plasticoins received by the company, it can claim tax benefits under a 2019 law passed in the country.\n	2021-04-28 06:24:46.491745+00	2021-10-04 15:28:47.529834+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.plasticoin.com.uy/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_039.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_39_logo.png	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
52	The Sea Cleaners: Deep water vessel capable of collecting large quantities of macro plastic waste from the sea	2016	250	Non-Profit Org	Pilot	f	\N	national	[]	Sea Cleaners is an association that wants to tackle marine plastic pollution. They aim to remove the plastic out of water, in high density areas (coasts, estuaries) before it breaks down into microplastic, and the chemicals leach out, harming the marine life and people. They also want to decrease the large amounts of plastic waste in the oceans.\n\nThe boat that will be used is called Manta, as it draws its inspiration from the mantis, and its large mouth. The Manta is meant for operations in open sea. It will be a floating factory that collects, sorts, compacts and stores plastic waste. Mantas will have three collecting treadmills between the hulls of the ship to scoop up big quantities of plastics. By compacting the waste, the Manta will be able to accommodate large quantities of waste and is estimated to hold 250 tons of waste. This will then be carried back to land and forwarded to relevant recycling centers. Besides cleaning the oceans, this project aims to conduct scientific observation, and involve itself in prevention of pollution, in education and achieving a circular economy.\n\nThe MANTA is based on the most advanced technologies in terms of clean energy, design, naval architecture, waste collection and treatment at sea. However, this is still work in progress, and they want more partners who will get involved and help in improving the design of the boat. The company is also looking for technical and financial partners to take the project forward. Feasibility studies have been carried out for eighteen months and a model ship is nearly ready.\n\nSea Cleaners was founded in 2016 by Yvan Bourgnon, a French Swiss explorer, and is based in France. Sea Cleaners work has already won it approval from The Prince Albert II of Monaco Foundation who are interested in environment protection.	2021-04-28 06:24:46.744198+00	2021-10-04 15:28:49.905429+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.theseacleaners.org/en/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_052.jpg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_52_logo.jpg	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
45	Seabin Smart Tech including Pollution Index: Autonomous floating waste collection device for harbors, coastlines and waterways	2015	\N	Startup	In market	t	contact@seabinproject.com	regional	[]	Description: Seabin focus on Clean Up and Prevention\n \nFor Clean Up:\nSeabin smart tech is used as an active water based capturing technology. The Seabin unit is installed in a strategic upstream location where marine litter converges naturally. Generally Ports, Marinas and City foreshores are the main installation points. Each unit filters 600,000 litres of water per day for micro plastics, oil, surface pollutants and general plastics including plastic fibers. Currently the global average capture is 3.9Kgs per day or 1.4 tons of marine litter per year. The cost to filter 600,000 litres of water is AUD$3.31 per day. The units are also solar compatible.\nThe next Seabin 6.0 is currently in production and will be incorporating under water sensors to monitor electrical conductivity, dissolvable oxygen and water temp as baseline data. The sensor technology is also designed as an appendage to be swapped out for other more relevant sensors to that region.\n \nSeabin are now offering services for citys and governments which not only include the daily empties and quarterly maintenance, but also the weekly data sets for the Pollution Index\n \nFor Prevention:\nSeabin Foundation use education and community initiatives combined with the Pollution Index data monitoring program.\nThe Pollution Index (PI) program is operational in 19 countries with a network of 71 volunteers uploading data sets weekly of what the Seabin smart tech is capturing.\nCurrently a Pollution Index data app is being developed and will be operational by December 2020.\n\nPlastic recovery capacity: Daily: 3.9 kgs per unit\nPer Year  1.4 tons per unit\n \nGlobal fleet is 860 units- daily capture is 3.6 tons per day and 500 million litres of water filtered per day\n \nEach unit has the capacity to catch:\n90,000 plastic bags / year\n35,700 coffee cups / year\n16,500 plastic water bottle s/ year\n166,500 plastic utensils	2021-04-28 06:24:46.602978+00	2022-11-09 08:05:50.496067+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	http://seabinproject.com/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_045.png	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_45_logo.jpg	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	f	en	f	gpml
